Hole in the Middle of High-Dimensional Data ¶

Here we will demonstrate that the data points in high-dimensional space become concentrated on the surface and leave tha center empty. For simulating high-dimensional data uniformly distributed on a p-dimensional ball we will use the following principle adopted from this https://blogs.sas.com/content/iml/2016/04/06/generate-points-uniformly-in-ball.html great blog post:

If Y is drawn from the uncorrelated multivariate normal distribution, then S = Y / ||Y|| has the uniform distribution on the unit d-sphere. Multiplying S by U1/d, where U has the uniform distribution on the unit interval (0,1), creates the uniform distribution in the unit d-dimensional ball.

This procedure reminds a generalization of the famous Box-Mueller transform for the random number generator https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Box%E2%80%93Muller_transform. Here we will start with simulating Y, normalizing it and generating X = (Y / norm(Y)) * U ^ (1 / p), where U ~ U[0,1], please see below:

Now let us normalize coordinates of each data point (vector) by the distance of the point from the center (0, 0) of the coordinates system. Here is the definition of normalized vectors https://mathworld.wolfram.com/NormalizedVector.html. As a result we will get a unit vector of data points.

$$ Y = \begin{pmatrix} x_1 & y_1\\ x_2 & y_2 \\ \dotsm & \dotsm \\ x_n & y_n \end{pmatrix} \Rightarrow \begin{pmatrix} \frac{x_1}{\sqrt{(x_1-0)^2+(y_1-0)^2}} & \frac{y_1}{\sqrt{(x_1-0)^2+(y_1-0)^2}}\\ \frac{x_2}{\sqrt{(x_2-0)^2+(y_2-0)^2}} & \frac{y_2}{\sqrt{(x_2-0)^2+(y_2-0)^2}} \\ \dotsm & \dotsm \\ \frac{x_n}{\sqrt{(x_n-0)^2+(y_n-0)^2}} & \frac{y_n}{\sqrt{(x_n-0)^2+(y_n-0)^2}} \end{pmatrix} $$

We can see that increasing the dimensionality of the data leads to shifting the data distribution from the center of the p-dimensional ball to the surface with the formation of a "hole" in the middle.

Pairwise Distances for High-Dimensional Data ¶

Here we will compute pairwise distances between data points for high-dimensional data and demonstrate that the distances increase as $\sqrt{p}$, where p is the number of dimensions.

In [31]:
from sklearn.metrics.pairwise import euclidean_distances

n = 1000

mean_dist = []
std_dist = []
for p in range(2, 500, 1):

    Y = np.random.randn(n, p)
    dist = euclidean_distances(Y, Y)
    
    mean_dist.append(np.mean(dist))
    std_dist.append(np.std(dist))

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.metrics.pairwise import euclidean_distances

n = 1000

my_dist = []
my_dims = []
for p in [2, 32, 512]:

    Y = np.random.randn(n, p)
    
    my_dist.append(list((euclidean_distances(Y, Y) / np.max(euclidean_distances(Y, Y))).flatten()))
    my_dims.append([str(p)]*(n*n))

dist_df = pd.DataFrame({'DIST': [item for sublist in my_dist for item in sublist], 
                        'DIMS': [item for sublist in my_dims for item in sublist]})

Now we will check how the distance between each data point and its nearest / middle / farthest neighbor changes with dimensionality of the data.

In [27]:
from sklearn.metrics.pairwise import euclidean_distances

n = 1000
p_min = 2
p_max = 1000

mean_nearest_n_dist = []
mean_middle_n_dist = []
mean_farthest_n_dist = []
for p in range(p_min, p_max, 1):

    Y = np.random.randn(n, p)
    dist = euclidean_distances(Y, Y)
    
    nearest_n_dist = []
    middle_n_dist = []
    farthest_n_dist = []
    for j in range(dist.shape[0]):
        
        sorted_dist = np.sort(dist[j,:])
        
        nearest_n_dist.append(sorted_dist[1])
        middle_n_dist.append(np.median(sorted_dist))
        farthest_n_dist.append(sorted_dist[-1])
        
    mean_nearest_n_dist.append(np.mean(nearest_n_dist))
    mean_middle_n_dist.append(np.mean(middle_n_dist))
    mean_farthest_n_dist.append(np.mean(farthest_n_dist))

Let us now check how Pearson correlations between data points (samples) changes with increasing dimensionality of the data.

In [68]:
n = 1000
p_min = 2
p_max = 500

max_corr = []
for p in range(p_min, p_max, 1):

    Y = np.random.randn(n, p)
    
    corr_matrix = np.corrcoef(Y)
    np.fill_diagonal(corr_matrix, 0)
    max_corr.append(np.max(corr_matrix))
    
plt.figure(figsize = (20, 15))
plt.plot(range(p_min, p_max, 1), max_corr, '-o')
plt.title('Decrease of max Pearson correlation between samples with increase of dimensionality', fontsize = 22)
plt.xlabel('Number of dimensions', fontsize = 22)
plt.ylabel('Max Pearson Correlation Coefficient', fontsize = 22)
plt.show()
In [ ]:
In [ ]:

We can see that samples become less ans less correlated with increasing the dimensionality of the data. For example, at dimensionality p > 100, we do not see any pair of samples correlated stronger than Pearson rho = 0.5, this is a very weak correlation. this means that in high dimensions, samples stop grouping with each other and become more and more independent from each other.

Loss of Information When Reducing Dimensions ¶

Here we will discuss to what extent we loose the original information when performing dimensionality reduction on a data set. We consider two types of symmetry in the data, which results in very different information loss. Let us generate a data set with 2 dimensions and 3 equidistant clusters. We generate the 2D clusters in such a way that both dimensions are important, i.e. triangle symmetry. Therefore reducing dimensions will lead to incorrect distances between clusters.

In [179]:
from mpl_toolkits import mplot3d

n = 1000
p = 3

X1 = np.random.randn(n, p)

X3 = X1 - np.max(X1)*2
X3[:,1] = X3[:,1] + np.max(X1)*4
X = np.vstack([X1, X2, X3])
y = np.array([['blue']*n, ['red']*n, ['green']*n])
y = y.flatten()

Here we can observe that if we consider only PC1, tSNE1 or UMAP1, the distances between the clusters will be violated compared to their original values, so we can not really reduce dimensions from the 2D down to 1D without loosing information about mutual positions of the clusters.

Let us now check the case of data with intrinsic one dimension. In this case we can very well reduce dimensions without loosing information. In other words, the dimensionality reduction techniques will preserve original distances between the 3 clusters.

plt.xlabel("Dimension 1", fontsize = 22); plt.ylabel("Dimension 2", fontsize = 22)

#PCA RECONSTRUCTION
plt.subplot(222)
X_reduced = PCA(n_components = 2).fit_transform(X)
plt.scatter(X_reduced[:, 0], X_reduced[:, 1], c = y, s = 50)
plt.title('Principal Component Analysis (PCA)', fontsize = 25)
plt.xlabel("PCA1", fontsize = 22); plt.ylabel("PCA2", fontsize = 22)

#TSNE RECONSTRUCTION
plt.subplot(223)
model = TSNE(learning_rate = 200, n_components = 2, random_state = 123, perplexity = 1000, 
             init = X_reduced, n_iter = 1000, verbose = 2)
tsne = model.fit_transform(X)
plt.scatter(tsne[:, 0], tsne[:, 1], c = y, s = 50)
plt.title('tSNE', fontsize = 25); plt.xlabel("tSNE1", fontsize = 22); plt.ylabel("tSNE2", fontsize = 22)

#UMAP RECONSTRUCTION
plt.subplot(224)
model = UMAP(learning_rate = 1, n_components = 2, min_dist = 1, n_neighbors = 1000, 
             init = X_reduced, n_epochs = 1000, verbose = 2)
umap = model.fit_transform(X)
plt.scatter(umap[:, 0], umap[:, 1], c = y, s = 50)
plt.title('UMAP', fontsize = 25); plt.xlabel("UMAP1", fontsize = 22); plt.ylabel("UMAP2", fontsize = 22)

In contrast to the previous example, considering just PC1, tSNE1 or UMAP1 will correctly preserve the inter-cluster distances. Therefore we can reduce dimensions from the original 2D down to 1D without loosing information about mutual positions of the clusters.

Random Matrices and Distributions of Eigenvalues ¶

Let us display distributions of eigen values for different ratios of n and p:

In [72]:
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA

n = [10000, 1000, 1000]
p = [1000, 1000, 10000]

eigen = []
np_ratio = []
for i in range(len(n)):
    
    X = np.random.randn(n[i], p[i])
    pca = PCA().fit(X)
    
    eigen.append(list(pca.explained_variance_))
    np_ratio.append([str(n[i] / p[i])]*min(n[i], p[i]))
    
eigen_df = pd.DataFrame({'EIGEN': [item for sublist in eigen for item in sublist], 
                        'NP_RATIO': [item for sublist in np_ratio for item in sublist]})

eigen_df['DIMENSION'] = np.where(eigen_df['NP_RATIO'] == '10.0','P << N', 
                           np.where(eigen_df['NP_RATIO'] == '1.0', 'P ~ N', 'P >> N'))

#eigen_df['EIGEN'] = np.log10(eigen_df['EIGEN'] + 1)

eigen_df
